com.apriori.collections

Interface GrowableArray<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the array
    All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<E>, SizedIterable<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractGrowableArray, ArrayListGrowableArray, NoCopyGrowableArray

    public interface GrowableArray<E>
extends SizedIterable<E>
    A container type that is like an array except that its capacity can change over time. This interface is intentionally much more narrow than List, which is its closest cousin from the Java Collections Framework. The abstract operations basically match that of an array with two exceptions: growBy(int) and shrinkBy(int). There are several additional methods with default implementations but notably absent are methods that allow for insertion into or removal from the beginning or middle of the array.

    Since this is a generic type, it does not have the type co-variance of actual Java arrays, and so behaves more like a Collection from that standpoint.

      • growBy

        void growBy(int numNewElements)
        Grows the capacity of the array by the given number of elements. The extra capacity as added to the end of the array. The new positions in the array will initially have a value of null.
        Parameters:
        numNewElements - the number of new elements by which to grow this array
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given number of elements is negative

      • shrinkBy

        void shrinkBy(int numRemovedElements)
        Shrinks the capacity of the array by the given number of elements. The capacity is taken from the end of the array, and any values contained in those last positions are implicitly removed.
        Parameters:
        numRemovedElements - the number of elements by which to shrink this array
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given number of elements is negative or is greater than the size of this array
